# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mac-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] Ethernet is the primary network protocol in data centers for computer-to-computer communications.
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] However, Ethernet is designed to be a best-effort network that may experience packet loss when the network or devices are busy.
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] Under the end-to-end principle, transport reliability in IP networks is the responsibility of a transport protocol, such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] One area of evolution for Ethernet is to add extensions to the existing protocol suite to provide reliability without requiring the complexity of TCP.
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] With the move to 10 Gbit/s and faster transmission rates, there is also a desire for finer granularity in control of bandwidth allocation and to ensure it is used more effectively.
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] These enhancements are particularly important to make Ethernet a more viable transport for storage and server cluster traffic.
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] A primary motivation is the sensitivity of Fibre Channel over Ethernet to frame loss.
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] The higher level goal is to use a single set of Ethernet physical devices or adapters for computers to talk to a storage area network (SAN), local area network (LAN) and InfiniBand fabric.
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] DCB aims, for selected traffic, to eliminate loss due to queue overflow (sometimes called **lossless Ethernet**) and to be able to allocate bandwidth on links.
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] Essentially, DCB enables, to some extent, the treatment of different priorities as if they were different pipes.
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] To meet these goals new standards are being (or have been) developed that either extend the existing set of Ethernet protocols or emulate the connectivity offered by Ethernet protocols.
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] Enabling DCB broadly on arbitrary networks with irregular topologies and without special routing may cause deadlocks, large buffering delays, unfairness and head-of-line blocking.
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] It was suggested to use DCB to eliminate TCP slow start using the approach of **TCP-Bolt**.
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] These new protocols required new hardware and software in both the network and the network interface controller.
[src:mac-security/data-center-bridging] Products were being developed by companies such as Avaya, Brocade, Cisco, Dell, EMC, Emulex, HP, Huawei, IBM, and Qlogic.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] For example, in IEEE 802.11 (Wi-Fi) the WPA and WPA2 standards have adopted IEEE 802.1X (with various EAP types) as the canonical authentication mechanism.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP is an authentication framework, not a specific authentication mechanism.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] It provides some common functions and negotiation of authentication methods called EAP methods.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] There are currently about 40 different methods defined.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Methods defined in IETF RFCs include EAP-MD5, EAP-POTP, EAP-GTC, EAP-TLS, EAP-IKEv2, EAP-SIM, EAP-AKA, and EAP-AKA'.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Additionally, a number of vendor-specific methods and new proposals exist.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Commonly used modern methods capable of operating in wireless networks include EAP-TLS, EAP-SIM, EAP-AKA, LEAP and EAP-TTLS.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Requirements for EAP methods used in wireless LAN authentication are described in RFC 4017.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The list of type and packets codes used in EAP is available from the IANA EAP Registry.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The standard also describes the conditions under which the AAA key management requirements described in RFC 4962 can be satisfied.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The Lightweight Extensible Authentication Protocol (LEAP) method was developed by Cisco Systems prior to the IEEE ratification of the 802.11i security standard.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco distributed the protocol through the CCX (Cisco Certified Extensions) as part of getting 802.1X and dynamic WEP adoption into the industry in the absence of a standard.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] There is no native support for LEAP in any Windows operating system, but it is widely supported by third-party client software most commonly included with WLAN (wireless LAN) devices.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] LEAP support for Microsoft Windows 7 and Microsoft Windows Vista can be added by downloading a client add in from Cisco that provides support for both LEAP and EAP-FAST.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Due to the wide adoption of LEAP in the networking industry many other WLAN vendors claim support for LEAP.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] LEAP uses a modified version of MS-CHAP, an authentication protocol in which user credentials are not strongly protected and easily compromised; an exploit tool called ASLEAP was released in early 2004 by Joshua Wright.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco recommends that customers who absolutely must use LEAP do so only with sufficiently complex passwords, though complex passwords are difficult to administer and enforce.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco's current recommendation is to use newer and stronger EAP protocols such as EAP-FAST, PEAP, or EAP-TLS.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Transport Layer Security (EAP-TLS), defined in RFC 5216, is an IETF open standard that uses the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol, and is well-supported among wireless vendors.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TLS is the original, standard wireless LAN EAP authentication protocol.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TLS is still considered one of the most secure EAP standards available, although TLS provides strong security only as long as the user understands potential warnings about false credentials, and is universally supported by all manufacturers of wireless LAN hardware and software.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Until April 2005, EAP-TLS was the only EAP type vendors needed to certify for a WPA or WPA2 logo.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] There are client and server implementations of EAP-TLS in 3Com, Apple, Avaya, Brocade Communications, Cisco, Enterasys Networks, Fortinet, Foundry, Hirschmann, HP, Juniper, Microsoft, and open source operating systems.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TLS is natively supported in Mac OS X 10.3 and above, wpa_supplicant, Windows 2000 SP4, Windows XP and above, Windows Mobile 2003 and above, Windows CE 4.2, and Apple's iOS mobile operating system.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Unlike most TLS implementations of HTTPS, such as on the World Wide Web, the majority of implementations of EAP-TLS require mutual authentication using client-side X.509 certificates without giving the option to disable the requirement, even though the standard does not mandate their use.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Some have identified this as having the potential to dramatically reduce adoption of EAP-TLS and prevent "open" but encrypted access points.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] This would allow for situations much like HTTPS, where a wireless hotspot allows free access and does not authenticate station clients but station clients wish to use encryption (IEEE 802.11i-2004 i.e.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] WPA2) and potentially authenticate the wireless hotspot.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] There have also been proposals to use IEEE 802.11u for access points to signal that they allow EAP-TLS using only server-side authentication, using the standard EAP-TLS IETF type instead of a vendor-specific EAP type.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The requirement for a client-side certificate, however unpopular it may be, is what gives EAP-TLS its authentication strength and illustrates the classic convenience vs. security trade-off.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] With a client-side certificate, a compromised password is not enough to break into EAP-TLS enabled systems because the intruder still needs to have the client-side certificate; indeed, a password is not even needed, as it is only used to encrypt the client-side certificate for storage.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The highest security available is when the "private keys" of client-side certificate are housed in smart cards.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] This is because there is no way to steal a client-side certificate's corresponding private key from a smart card without stealing the card itself.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is more likely that the physical theft of a smart card would be noticed (and the smart card immediately revoked) than a (typical) password theft would be noticed.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] In addition, the private key on a smart card is typically encrypted using a PIN that only the owner of the smart card knows, minimizing its utility for a thief even before the card has been reported stolen and revoked.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-MD5 was the only IETF Standards Track based EAP method when it was first defined in the original RFC for EAP, RFC 2284.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] It offers minimal security; the MD5 hash function is vulnerable to dictionary attacks, and does not support key generation, which makes it unsuitable for use with dynamic WEP, or WPA/WPA2 enterprise.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-MD5 differs from other EAP methods in that it only provides authentication of the EAP peer to the EAP server but not mutual authentication.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] By not providing EAP server authentication, this EAP method is vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-MD5 support was first included in Windows 2000 and deprecated in Windows Vista.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Protected One-Time Password (EAP-POTP), which is described in RFC 4793, is an EAP method developed by RSA Laboratories that uses one-time password (OTP) tokens, such as a handheld hardware device or a hardware or software module running on a personal computer, to generate authentication keys.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-POTP can be used to provide unilateral or mutual authentication and key material in protocols that use EAP.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP-POTP method provides two-factor user authentication, meaning that a user needs both physical access to a token and knowledge of a personal identification number (PIN) to perform authentication.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Pre-shared key (EAP-PSK), defined in RFC 4764, is an EAP method for mutual authentication and session key derivation using a pre-shared key (PSK).
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] It provides a protected communication channel, when mutual authentication is successful, for both parties to communicate and is designed for authentication over insecure networks such as IEEE 802.11.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-PSK is documented in an experimental RFC that provides a lightweight and extensible EAP method that does not require any public-key cryptography.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP method protocol exchange is done in a minimum of four messages.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Password (EAP-PWD), defined in RFC 5931, is an EAP method which uses a shared password for authentication.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The password may be a low-entropy one and may be drawn from some set of possible passwords, like a dictionary, which is available to an attacker.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The underlying key exchange is resistant to active attack, passive attack, and dictionary attack.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-PWD is in the base of Android 4.0 (ICS).
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is in FreeRADIUS and Radiator RADIUS servers, and it is in hostapd and wpa_supplicant.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Tunneled Transport Layer Security (EAP-TTLS) is an EAP protocol that extends TLS.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] It was co-developed by Funk Software and Certicom and is widely supported across platforms.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Microsoft did not incorporate native support for the EAP-TTLS protocol in Windows XP, Vista, or 7.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Supporting TTLS on these platforms requires third-party Encryption Control Protocol (ECP) certified software.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Microsoft Windows started EAP-TTLS support with Windows 8, support for EAP-TTLS appeared in Windows Phone version 8.1.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The client can, but does not have to be authenticated via a CA-signed PKI certificate to the server.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] This greatly simplifies the setup procedure since a certificate is not needed on every client.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] After the server is securely authenticated to the client via its CA certificate and optionally the client to the server, the server can then use the established secure connection ("tunnel") to authenticate the client.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] It can use an existing and widely deployed authentication protocol and infrastructure, incorporating legacy password mechanisms and authentication databases, while the secure tunnel provides protection from eavesdropping and man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Note that the user's name is never transmitted in unencrypted clear text, improving privacy.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Two distinct versions of EAP-TTLS exist: original EAP-TTLS (a.k.a.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TTLSv0 is described in RFC 5281, EAP-TTLSv1 is available as an Internet draft.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] 2 (EAP-IKEv2) is an EAP method based on the Internet Key Exchange protocol version 2 (IKEv2).
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] It provides mutual authentication and session key establishment between an EAP peer and an EAP server.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] bit strings that are known to both the server and the peer.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] High-entropy bit strings that are known to both the server and the peer.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is possible to use a different authentication credential (and thereby technique) in each direction.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] For example, the EAP server authenticates itself using public/private key pair and the EAP peer using symmetric key.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] However, not all of the nine theoretical combinations are expected in practice.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Specifically, the standard RFC 5106 lists four use cases: The server authenticating with an asymmetric key pair while the client uses any of the three methods; and that both sides use a symmetric key.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-IKEv2 is described in RFC 5106, and a prototype implementation exists.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Flexible Authentication via Secure Tunneling (EAP-FAST; RFC 4851) is a protocol proposal by Cisco Systems as a replacement for LEAP.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The protocol was designed to address the weaknesses of LEAP while preserving the "lightweight" implementation.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Use of server certificates is optional in EAP-FAST.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-FAST uses a Protected Access Credential (PAC) to establish a TLS tunnel in which client credentials are verified.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] When automatic PAC provisioning is enabled, EAP-FAST has a vulnerability where an attacker can intercept the PAC and use that to compromise user credentials.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] This vulnerability is mitigated by manual PAC provisioning or by using server certificates for the PAC provisioning phase.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is worth noting that the PAC file is issued on a per-user basis.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] This is a requirement in RFC 4851 sec 7.4.4 so if a new user logs on the network from a device, a new PAC file must be provisioned first.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] This is one reason why it is difficult not to run EAP-FAST in insecure anonymous provisioning mode.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The alternative is to use device passwords instead, but then the device is validated on the network not the user.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-FAST can be used without PAC files, falling back to normal TLS.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-FAST is natively supported in Apple OS X 10.4.8 and newer.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco supplies an EAP-FAST module for Windows Vista and later operating systems which have an extensible EAPHost architecture for new authentication methods and supplicants.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Tunnel Extensible Authentication Protocol (TEAP; RFC 7170) is a tunnel-based EAP method that enables secure communication between a peer and a server by using the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol to establish a mutually authenticated tunnel.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Within the tunnel, TLV (Type-Length-Value) objects are used to convey authentication-related data between the EAP peer and the EAP server.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] In addition to peer authentication, TEAP allows the peer to ask the server for a certificate by sending a request in PKCS#10 format.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] After receiving the certificate request and authenticating the peer, the server can provision a certificate to the peer in PKCS#7 format (RFC 2325).
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The server can also distribute trusted root certificates to the peer in PKCS#7 format (RFC 2325).
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Both operations are enclosed into the corresponding TLVs and happen securely within the already established TLS tunnel.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Subscriber Identity Module (EAP-SIM) is used for authentication and session key distribution using the subscriber identity module (SIM) from the Global System for Mobile Communications (GSM).
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] GSM cellular networks use a subscriber identity module card to carry out user authentication.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-SIM uses a SIM authentication algorithm between the client and an Authentication, Authorization and Accounting (AAA) server providing mutual authentication between the client and the network.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] In EAP-SIM the communication between the SIM card and the Authentication Centre (AuC) replaces the need for a pre-established password between the client and the AAA server.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The A3/A8 algorithms are being run a few times, with different 128 bit challenges, so there will be more 64 bit Kc-s which will be combined/mixed to create stronger keys (Kc-s won't be used directly).
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The lack of mutual authentication in GSM has also been overcome.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Extensible Authentication Protocol Method for Universal Mobile Telecommunications System (UMTS) Authentication and Key Agreement (EAP-AKA), is an EAP mechanism for authentication and session key distribution using the UMTS Subscriber Identity Module (USIM).
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP-AKA' variant of EAP-AKA, defined in RFC 5448, and is used for non-3GPP access to a 3GPP core network.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Generic Token Card, or EAP-GTC, is an EAP method created by Cisco as an alternative to PEAPv0/EAP-MSCHAPv2 and defined in RFC 2284 and RFC 3748.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-GTC carries a text challenge from the authentication server, and a reply generated by a security token.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The PEAP-GTC authentication mechanism allows generic authentication to a number of databases such as Novell Directory Service (NDS) and Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP), as well as the use of a one-time password.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP with the encrypted key exchange, or EAP-EKE, is one of the few EAP methods that provide secure mutual authentication using short passwords and no need for public key certificates.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is a three-round exchange, based on the Diffie-Hellman variant of the well-known EKE protocol.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Nimble out-of-band authentication for EAP (EAP-NOOB) is a generic bootstrapping solution for devices which have no pre-configured authentication credentials and which are not yet registered on any server.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is especially useful for Internet-of-Things (IoT) gadgets and toys that come with no information about any owner, network or server.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Authentication for this EAP method is based on a user-assisted out-of-band (OOB) channel between the server and peer.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-NOOB supports many types of OOB channels such as QR codes, NFC tags, audio etc. and unlike other EAP methods, the protocol security has been verified by formal modeling of the specification with ProVerif and MCRL2 tools.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-NOOB performs an Ephemeral Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellman (ECDHE) over the in-band EAP channel.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The user then confirms this exchange by transferring the OOB message.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Users can transfer the OOB message from the peer to the server, when for example, the device is a smart TV that can show a QR code.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Alternatively, users can transfer the OOB message from the server to the peer, when for example, the device being bootstrapped is a camera that can only read a QR code.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP is not a wire protocol; instead it only defines message formats.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Each protocol that uses EAP defines a way to encapsulate EAP messages within that protocol's messages.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The encapsulation of EAP over IEEE 802 is defined in IEEE 802.1X and known as "EAP over LANs" or EAPOL.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAPOL was originally designed for IEEE 802.3 Ethernet in 802.1X-2001, but was clarified to suit other IEEE 802 LAN technologies such as IEEE 802.11 wireless and Fiber Distributed Data Interface (ANSI X3T9.5/X3T12, adopted as ISO 9314) in 802.1X-2004.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAPOL protocol was also modified for use with IEEE 802.1AE (MACsec) and IEEE 802.1AR (Initial Device Identity, IDevID) in 802.1X-2010.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The Protected Extensible Authentication Protocol, also known as Protected EAP or simply PEAP, is a protocol that encapsulates EAP within a potentially encrypted and authenticated Transport Layer Security (TLS) tunnel.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The purpose was to correct deficiencies in EAP; EAP assumed a protected communication channel, such as that provided by physical security, so facilities for protection of the EAP conversation were not provided.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAP was jointly developed by Cisco Systems, Microsoft, and RSA Security.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAPv0 was the version included with Microsoft Windows XP and was nominally defined in draft-kamath-pppext-peapv0-00.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAPv1 and PEAPv2 were defined in different versions of *draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap*.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAPv1 was defined in draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap-00 through draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap-05, and PEAPv2 was defined in versions beginning with draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap-06.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The protocol only specifies chaining multiple EAP mechanisms and not any specific method.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Use of the EAP-MSCHAPv2 and EAP-GTC methods are the most commonly supported.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] Both the RADIUS and Diameter AAA protocols can encapsulate EAP messages.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] They are often used by Network Access Server (NAS) devices to forward EAP packets between IEEE 802.1X endpoints and AAA servers to facilitate IEEE 802.1X.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The Protocol for Carrying Authentication for Network Access (PANA) is an IP-based protocol that allows a device to authenticate itself with a network to be granted access.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] PANA will not define any new authentication protocol, key distribution, key agreement or key derivation protocols; for these purposes, EAP will be used, and PANA will carry the EAP payload.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] PANA allows dynamic service provider selection, supports various authentication methods, is suitable for roaming users, and is independent from the link layer mechanisms.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP was originally an authentication extension for the Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP).
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] PPP has supported EAP since EAP was created as an alternative to the Challenge-Handshake Authentication Protocol (CHAP) and the Password Authentication Protocol (PAP), which were eventually incorporated into EAP.
[src:mac-security/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP extension to PPP was first defined in RFC 2284, now obsoleted by RFC 3748.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1ae] Key management and the establishment of secure associations is outside the scope of 802.1AE, but is specified by 802.1X-2010.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1ae] The 802.1AE standard specifies the implementation of a *MAC Security Entities* (SecY) that can be thought of as part of the stations attached to the same LAN, providing secure MAC service to the client.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1ae] The IEEE 802.1AE (MACsec) standard specifies a set of protocols to meet the security requirements for protecting data traversing Ethernet LANs.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1ae] MACsec allows unauthorized LAN connections to be identified and excluded from communication within the network.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1ae] In common with IPsec and TLS, MACsec defines a security infrastructure to provide data confidentiality, data integrity and data origin authentication.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1ae] By assuring that a frame comes from the station that claimed to have sent it, MACSec can mitigate attacks on Layer 2 protocols.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The standard directly addresses an attack technique called Hardware Addition where an attacker posing as a guest, customer or staff smuggles a hacking device into the building that they then plug into the network giving them full access.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] A notable example of the issue occurred in 2005 when a machine attached to Walmart's network hacked thousands of their servers.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] IEEE 802.1X defines the encapsulation of the Extensible Authentication Protocol (EAP) over wired IEEE 802 networks and over 802.11 wireless networks, which is known as "EAP over LAN" or EAPOL.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] EAPOL was originally specified for IEEE 802.3 Ethernet, IEEE 802.5 Token Ring, and FDDI (ANSI X3T9.5/X3T12 and ISO 9314) in 802.1X-2001, but was extended to suit other IEEE 802 LAN technologies such as IEEE 802.11 wireless in 802.1X-2004.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The EAPOL was also modified for use with IEEE 802.1AE ("MACsec") and IEEE 802.1AR (Secure Device Identity, DevID) in 802.1X-2010 to support service identification and optional point to point encryption over the internal LAN segment.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X is part of the logical link control (LLC) sublayer of the 802 reference model.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X authentication involves three parties: a supplicant, an authenticator, and an authentication server.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The **supplicant** is a client device (such as a laptop) that wishes to attach to the LAN/WLAN.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The term 'supplicant' is also used interchangeably to refer to the software running on the client that provides credentials to the authenticator.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Authentication servers typically run software supporting the RADIUS and EAP protocols.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] In some cases, the authentication server software may be running on the authenticator hardware.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator acts like a security guard to a protected network.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The supplicant (i.e., client device) is not allowed access through the authenticator to the protected side of the network until the supplicant's identity has been validated and authorized.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] With 802.1X port-based authentication, the supplicant must initially provide the required credentials to the authenticator - these will have been specified in advance by the network administrator and could include a user name/password or a permitted digital certificate.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator forwards these credentials to the authentication server to decide whether access is to be granted.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] If the authentication server determines the credentials are valid, it informs the authenticator, which in turn allows the supplicant (client device) to access resources located on the protected side of the network.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] EAPOL operates over the data link layer, and in Ethernet II framing protocol has an EtherType value of 0x888E.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X-2001 defines two logical port entities for an authenticated port—the "controlled port" and the "uncontrolled port".
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The controlled port is manipulated by the 802.1X PAE (Port Access Entity) to allow (in the authorized state) or prevent (in the unauthorized state) network traffic ingress and egress to/from the controlled port.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The uncontrolled port is used by the 802.1X PAE to transmit and receive EAPOL frames.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X-2004 defines the equivalent port entities for the supplicant; so a supplicant implementing 802.1X-2004 may prevent higher-level protocols from being used if it is not content that authentication has successfully completed.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] This is particularly useful when an EAP method providing mutual authentication is used, as the supplicant can prevent data leakage when connected to an unauthorized network.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] **Initiation** To initiate authentication the authenticator will periodically transmit EAP-Request Identity frames to a special Layer 2 MAC address (*01:80:C2:00:00:03*) on the local network segment.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The supplicant listens at this address, and on receipt of the EAP-Request Identity frame, it responds with an EAP-Response Identity frame containing an identifier for the supplicant such as a User ID.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator then encapsulates this Identity response in a RADIUS Access-Request packet and forwards it on to the authentication server.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The supplicant may also initiate or restart authentication by sending an EAPOL-Start frame to the authenticator, which will then reply with an EAP-Request Identity frame.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] **Negotiation** *(Technically EAP negotiation)* The authentication server sends a reply (encapsulated in a RADIUS Access-Challenge packet) to the authenticator, containing an EAP Request specifying the EAP Method (The type of EAP based authentication it wishes the supplicant to perform).
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator encapsulates the EAP Request in an EAPOL frame and transmits it to the supplicant.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] At this point, the supplicant can start using the requested EAP Method, or do a NAK ("Negative Acknowledgement") and respond with the EAP Methods it is willing to perform.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] If authentication is successful, the authenticator sets the port to the "authorized" state and normal traffic is allowed.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] If it is unsuccessful, the port remains in the "unauthorized" state.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] When the supplicant logs off, it sends an EAPOL-logoff message to the authenticator, the authenticator then sets the port to the "unauthorized" state, once again blocking all non-EAP traffic.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] An open-source project named Open1X produces a client, Xsupplicant.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] This client is currently available for both Linux and Windows.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The main drawbacks of the Open1X client are that it does not provide comprehensible and extensive user documentation and that most Linux vendors do not provide a package for it.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The more general wpa_supplicant can be used for 802.11 wireless networks and wired networks.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Both support a very wide range of EAP types.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] ChromeOS has supported 802.1X since mid-2011.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Avenda Systems provides a supplicant for Windows, Linux and macOS.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] They also have a plugin for the Microsoft NAP framework.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Avenda also offers health checking agents.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Windows defaults to not responding to 802.1X authentication requests for 20 minutes after a failed authentication.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] This can cause significant disruption to clients.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The block period can be configured using the HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\dot3svc\BlockTime DWORD value (HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\wlansvc\BlockTime for wireless networks) in the registry (entered in minutes).
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] A hotfix is required for Windows XP SP3 and Windows Vista SP2 to make the period configurable.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Wildcard server certificates are not supported by EAPHost, the Windows component that provides EAP support in the operating system.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The implication of this is that when using a commercial certification authority, individual certificates must be purchased.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Windows XP has major issues with its handling of IP address changes resulting from user-based 802.1X authentication that changes the VLAN and thus subnet of clients.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Microsoft has stated that it will not backport the SSO feature from Vista that resolves these issues.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] If users are not logging in with roaming profiles, a hotfix must be downloaded and installed if authenticating via PEAP with PEAP-MSCHAPv2.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Windows Vista-based computers that are connected via an IP phone may not authenticate as expected and, as a result, the client can be placed into the wrong VLAN.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Windows 7 based computers that are connected via an IP phone may not authenticate as expected and, consequently, the client can be placed into the wrong VLAN.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Windows 7 does not respond to 802.1X authentication requests after initial 802.1X authentication fails.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Windows PE does not have native support for 802.1X.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] However, support can be added to WinPE 2.1 and WinPE 3.0 through hotfixes that are available from Microsoft.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Although full documentation is not yet available, preliminary documentation for the use of these hotfixes is available via a Microsoft blog.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Most Linux distributions support 802.1X via wpa_supplicant and desktop integration like NetworkManager.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The iPhone and iPod Touch support 802.1X since the release of iOS 2.0. macOS has offered native support since Mac OS X Panther.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] As of iOS 17 and macOS 14, Apple devices support connecting to 802.1X networks using EAP-TLS with TLS 1.3 (EAP-TLS 1.3).
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Additionally, devices running iOS/iPadOS/tvOS 17 or later support wired 802.1X networks.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Android has support for 802.1X since the release of 1.6 Donut.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] eduroam (the international roaming service), mandates the use of 802.1X authentication when providing network access to guests visiting from other eduroam-enabled institutions.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] BT (British Telecom, PLC) employs Identity Federation for authentication in services delivered to a wide variety of industries and governments.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Not all devices support 802.1X authentication.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Examples include network printers, Ethernet-based electronics like environmental sensors, cameras, and wireless phones.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] For those devices to be used in a protected network environment, alternative mechanisms must be provided to authenticate them.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] One option would be to disable 802.1X on that port, but that leaves that port unprotected and open for abuse.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Another slightly more reliable option is to use the MAB option.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] When MAB is configured on a port, that port will first try to check if the connected device is 802.1X compliant, and if no reaction is received from the connected device, it will try to authenticate with the AAA server using the connected device's MAC address as username and password.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The network administrator then must make provisions on the RADIUS server to authenticate those MAC addresses, either by adding them as regular users or implementing additional logic to resolve them in a network inventory database.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Many managed Ethernet switches offer options for this.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] In the summer of 2005, Microsoft's Steve Riley posted an article (based on the original research of Microsoft MVP Svyatoslav Pidgorny) detailing a serious vulnerability in the 802.1X protocol, involving a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] Riley suggests that for wired networks the use of IPsec or a combination of IPsec and 802.1X would be more secure.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] EAPOL-Logoff frames transmitted by the 802.1X supplicant are sent in the clear and contain no data derived from the credential exchange that initially authenticated the client.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] They are therefore trivially easy to spoof on shared media and can be used as part of a targeted DoS on both wired and wireless LANs.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] In an EAPOL-Logoff attack, a malicious third party with access to the medium the authenticator is attached to repeatedly sends forged EAPOL-Logoff frames from the target device's MAC Address.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator (believing that the targeted device wishes to end its authentication session) closes the target's authentication session, blocking traffic ingressing from the target, denying it access to the network.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The 802.1X-2010 specification, which began as 802.1af, addresses vulnerabilities in previous 802.1X specifications, by using MACsec IEEE 802.1AE to encrypt data between logical ports (running on top of a physical port) and IEEE 802.1AR (Secure Device Identity / DevID) authenticated devices.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] As a stopgap, until these enhancements are widely implemented, some vendors have extended the 802.1X-2001 and 802.1X-2004 protocol, allowing multiple concurrent authentication sessions to occur on a single port.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] While this prevents traffic from devices with unauthenticated MAC addresses ingressing on an 802.1X authenticated port, it will not stop a malicious device snooping on traffic from an authenticated device and provides no protection against MAC spoofing, or EAPOL-Logoff attacks.
[src:mac-security/ieee-802-1x] The IETF-backed alternative is the Protocol for Carrying Authentication for Network Access (PANA), which also carries EAP, although it works at layer 3, using UDP, thus not being tied to the 802 infrastructure.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] In IEEE 802 LAN/MAN standards, the **medium access control** (**MAC**), also called **media access control**, is the layer that controls the hardware responsible for interaction with the wired (electrical or optical) or wireless transmission medium.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] The MAC sublayer and the logical link control (LLC) sublayer together make up the data link layer.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] The LLC provides flow control and multiplexing for the logical link (i.e.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] EtherType, 802.1Q VLAN tag etc), while the MAC provides flow control and multiplexing for the transmission medium.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] These two sublayers together correspond to layer 2 of the OSI model.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] For compatibility reasons, LLC is optional for implementations of IEEE 802.3 (the frames are then "raw"), but compulsory for implementations of other IEEE 802 physical layer standards.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] Within the hierarchy of the OSI model and IEEE 802 standards, the MAC sublayer provides a control abstraction of the physical layer such that the complexities of physical link control are invisible to the LLC and upper layers of the network stack.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] Thus, any LLC sublayer (and higher layers) may be used with any MAC.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] In turn, the medium access control block is formally connected to the PHY via a media-independent interface.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] Although the MAC block is today typically integrated with the PHY within the same device package, historically any MAC could be used with any PHY, independent of the transmission medium.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] For topologies with a collision domain (bus, ring, mesh, point-to-multipoint topologies), the channel access method controls when data is sent and when waiting is necessary to avoid collisions.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] Additionally, the MAC is also responsible for compensating for collisions by initiating retransmission if a jam signal is detected.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] When receiving data from the physical layer, the MAC block ensures data integrity by verifying the sender's frame check sequences and strips off the sender's preamble and padding before passing the data up to the higher layers.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] The local network addresses used in IEEE 802 networks and FDDI networks are called *MAC addresses*; they are based on the addressing scheme that was used in early Ethernet implementations.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] A MAC address is intended as a unique serial number.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] MAC addresses are typically assigned to network interface hardware at the time of manufacture.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] The most significant part of the address identifies the manufacturer, who assigns the remainder of the address, thus providing a potentially unique address.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] This makes it possible for frames to be delivered on a network link that interconnects hosts by some combination of repeaters, hubs, bridges and switches, but not by network layer routers.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] Examples of physical networks are Ethernet networks and Wi-Fi networks, both of which are IEEE 802 networks and use IEEE 802 48-bit MAC addresses.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] A MAC layer is not required in full-duplex point-to-point communication, but address fields are included in some point-to-point protocols for compatibility reasons.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] The channel access control mechanisms provided by the MAC layer are also known as a multiple access method.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] This makes it possible for several stations connected to the same physical medium to share it.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] Examples of shared physical media are bus networks, ring networks, hub networks, wireless networks and half-duplex point-to-point links.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] The multiple access method may detect or avoid data packet collisions if a packet mode contention based channel access method is used, or reserve resources to establish a logical channel if a circuit-switched or channelization-based channel access method is used.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] The channel access control mechanism relies on a physical layer multiplex scheme.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] The most widespread multiple access method is the contention-based CSMA/CD used in Ethernet networks.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] This mechanism is only utilized within a network collision domain, for example, an Ethernet bus network or a hub-based star topology network.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] An Ethernet network may be divided into several collision domains, interconnected by bridges and switches.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] A multiple access method is not required in a switched full-duplex network, such as today's switched Ethernet networks, but is often available in the equipment for compatibility reasons.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] Use of directional antennas and millimeter-wave communication in a wireless personal area network increases the probability of concurrent scheduling of non‐interfering transmissions in a localized area, which results in an immense increase in network throughput.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] However, the optimum scheduling of concurrent transmission is an NP-hard problem.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] Cellular networks, such as GSM, UMTS or LTE networks, also use a MAC layer.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] The MAC protocol in cellular networks is designed to maximize the utilization of the expensive licensed spectrum.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] The air interface of a cellular network is at layers 1 and 2 of the OSI model; at layer 2, it is divided into multiple protocol layers.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] In UMTS and LTE, those protocols are the Packet Data Convergence Protocol (PDCP), the Radio Link Control (RLC) protocol, and the MAC protocol.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] The base station has absolute control over the air interface and schedules the downlink access as well as the uplink access of all devices.
[src:mac-security/media-access-control] The MAC protocol is specified by 3GPP in TS 25.321 for UMTS, TS 36.321 for LTE and TS 38.321 for 5G.
